le":"1150–Zesnulá","um 1170":"okolo 1170","1149":"1149","Abt 1194":"okolo 1194","about 1191":"okolo 1191","1168":"1168","1277":"1277","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, Warwickshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1170–1194":"1170–1194","1168–1193":"1168–1193","1191–Male":"1191–Afdød","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1196–Female":"1196–Afdød","1149–Male":"1149–Afdød","1150–Female":"1150–Afdød","um 1170":"omkring 1170","1149":"1149","Abt 1194":"omkring 1194","about 1191":"omkring 1191","1168":"1168","1277":"1277","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1170–1194":"1170–1194","1168–1193":"1168–1193","1191–Male":"1191–Overleden","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1196–Female":"1196–Overleden","1149–Male":"1149–Overleden","1150–Female":"1150–Overleden","um 1170":"circa 1170","1149":"1149","Abt 1194":"circa 1194","about 1191":"circa 1191","1168":"1168","1277":"1277","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1170–1194":"1170–1194","1168–1193":"1168–1193","1191–Male":"1191–Deceased","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1196–Female":"1196–Deceased","1149–Male":"1149–Deceased","1150–Female":"1150–Deceased","um 1170":"about 1170","1149":"1149","Abt 1194":"about 1194","about 1191":"about 1191","1168":"1168","1277":"1277","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clinton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Louth, Westmeath) and Scottish: shortened form of   McClinton  .","English: habitational name, either from Glympton in Oxfordshire, named as ‘settlement (Old English <i>tūn</i>) on the Glym river’, a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright stream’, or from Glinton in Northamptonshire, early recorded as <i>Clinton</i> (named with an unrecorded Old English element akin to Middle Low German <i>glinde</i> ‘enclosure, fence’ + Old English <i>tūn</i>). The surname was taken to Ireland in or before the 16th century.","History: Charles Clinton (born 1690 in Longford, Ireland) organized a group of colonists and founded the settlement of Little Britain, Ulster County, NY, in 1731. His son George Clinton (1739–1812) was governor of NY (1777–95), and they had many prominent descendants. — An English aristocratic family called <i>Clinton</i> was founded by Geoffrey de Clinton (flourished 1130), who held lands at Glympton, Oxfordshire. He was chamberlain and treasurer to Henry I (1100–35)."],"variants":[{"name":"McClinton","meanings":["Irish (northern) and Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Fhionntain</b> (Scottish), <b>Mac Giolla Fhionntáin</b> (Irish) ‘son of the servant (i.e. devotee) of (Saint) <i>Fionntan</i>’, whose name has been explained as ‘the white ancient’."]}]},{"name":"Joanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Joannah","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]},{"name":"Joana","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joanna Clinton was born in 1170, in Shirley, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Clinton of Essex, was 22 and her mother, Idonea de Saye, was 21. She married Henry Shirley in 1193, in Ettington, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1194, in her hometown, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1170–1194":"1170–1194","1168–1193":"1168–1193","1191–Male":"1191–Surnud","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1196–Female":"1196–Surnud","1149–Male":"1149–Surnud","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","um 1170":"umbes 1170","1149":"1149","Abt 1194":"umbes 1194","about 1191":"umbes 1191","1168":"1168","1277":"1277","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1170–1194":"1170–1194","1168–1193":"1168–1193","1191–Male":"1191–Kuollut","1194–1277":"1194–1277","1196–Female":"1196–Kuollut","1149–Male":"1149–Kuollut","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","um 1170":"noin 1170","1149":"1149","Abt 1194":"noin 1194","about 1191":"noin 1191","1168":"1168","1277":"1277","1196":"1196","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Shirley, Derbyshire, England":"Shirley, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Eatington, Warwickshire, England":"Ettington, War